The paper discusses probabilistic programming languages and inference mechanisms, which are typically associated with artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also introduces distributional clauses, which are an extension of Sato's distribution semantics, and discusses logic programming techniques such as magic sets and backward reasoning, which are associated with logic programming (cs.LO, cs.PL). The paper also discusses approximate inference methods and importance sampling, which are associated with machine learning and statistical inference (cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses the integration of backward reasoning to identify and avoid inconsistent regions of the sample space, which is associated with control and systems theory (cs.SY).
